	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nvxUnqZIM98YNt5-9",
			"markdown": "The Scholar seeks understanding in a universe filled with mysteries, systems, histories, and dangerous ideas. Whether you are a physicist unraveling alien technology, a historian reconstructing a fallen empire, a cryptographer breaking military codes, a xenologist studying unfamiliar cultures, or a conspiracy theorist hunting forbidden truths, you answer questions no one else can even ask. In many campaigns, the Scholar transforms confusion into knowledge, giving the group the context needed to survive, negotiate, innovate, or uncover what lies hidden beneath the surface of the setting.\n\nNot all Scholars live in universities or laboratories. Some are field researchers excavating ancient ruins under hostile skies, while others are intelligence analysts, corporate scientists, investigative anthropologists, AI theorists, cult experts, or information brokers. In cyberpunk settings, Scholars may specialize in machine learning, memetics, cryptography, economics, or sociological modeling. In space opera campaigns, they may study alien ecosystems, forgotten precursor civilizations, or dangerous anomalies recovered from deep space. Even in combat-heavy games, a Scholar provides strategic insight, technical expertise, and answers to problems brute force cannot solve.\n\n*Scientists* are researchers, engineers, and technical specialists who explain how the universe functions through experimentation, mathematics, and applied knowledge. Analytical Scientists emphasize Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics, Computer Programming, Engineering, Biology, or Weird Science, supported by Eidetic Memory, Mathematical Ability, Natural Scientist, Single-Minded, and Versatile. Whether designing experimental technology, reverse-engineering alien devices, solving ecological disasters, or building dangerous prototypes, Scientists thrive in campaigns centered on advanced technology, discovery, and scientific problem-solving. Their dedication to knowledge often comes with disadvantages such as Absent-Mindedness, Curious, Workaholic, Obsession, Low Empathy, or Overconfidence, as many Scientists become consumed by their research at the expense of practicality or social awareness.\n\n*Academics* are professors, historians, philosophers, linguists, archivists, and cultural experts who preserve, interpret, and communicate knowledge. Erudite Academics focus on History, Literature, Anthropology, Theology, Philosophy, Sociology, Psychology, Teaching, Writing, and Public Speaking, often supported by Language Talent, Voice, Cultural Adaptability, Good Reputation, Tenure, and Academic Talent. This archetype excels in diplomatic campaigns, political intrigue, historical mysteries, first-contact scenarios, and investigations involving culture, ideology, or ancient civilizations. Many Academics struggle outside their intellectual comfort zones, commonly taking disadvantages such as Chummy, Charitable, Curious, Truthfulness, Indecisive, Pacifism, Sense of Duty, or Shyness, reflecting intellectuals more comfortable debating ideas than surviving violence.\n\n*Field Scholars* are archaeologists, xenologists, survey researchers, and expedition specialists who pursue knowledge directly in dangerous environments. Adventurous Field Scholars emphasize Archaeology, Geography, Geology, Anthropology, Astronomy, Cartography, Observation, Search, Survival, and Spacer skills, supported by Intuition, Fearlessness, Luck, Cultural Adaptability, Serendipity, and Gizmo. Whether mapping hostile planets, excavating precursor ruins, cataloging alien species, or investigating impossible phenomena at the edge of known space, they bring knowledge back from places civilized people fear to enter. Their hunger for discovery often develops into disadvantages such as Curious, Fanaticism, Greed, Overconfidence, Stubbornness, Xenophilia, or Workaholic tendencies, as many Explorer-Scholars become obsessed with uncovering secrets no matter the danger.\n\n*Cryptics* are codebreakers, intelligence analysts, occult researchers, conspiracy hunters, and experts in dangerous information. Paranoid Cryptics focus on Cryptography, Computer Programming, Hidden Lore, Psychology, Sociology, Mathematics, Detect Lies, Expert Skill, and parascientific or paranormal disciplines, often supported by Intuition, Lightning Calculator, Eidetic Memory, Language Talent, and Parapsychologist. This archetype thrives in espionage games, information warfare, cosmic horror, cyberpunk conspiracies, and campaigns where forbidden knowledge itself becomes a threat. Many Cryptics pay a psychological or social price for what they know, commonly developing disadvantages such as Obsession, Clueless, Combat Paralysis, Gullibility, Paranoia, Xenophobia, Xenophilia, or various social stigmas and eccentricities tied to dangerous or forbidden knowledge.\n\nMany Scholars eventually branch beyond pure academia. Some become explorers, intelligence operatives, diplomats, engineers, propagandists, or investigators depending on the needs of the campaign. Others focus narrowly on a single discipline and become unmatched experts, while more versatile Scholars learn to combine technical expertise with social skill, field survival, or political influence. In dangerous settings, the Scholar who can survive hostile environments, recognize hidden threats, and communicate their discoveries clearly is often far more valuable than one who only understands theory in isolation."
		}
	]
}
